definition.value: An alanine derivative that is L-alanine bearing a 5-fluorouracil-1-yl substituent at position 3. A more potent and selective AMPA receptor agonist (at hGluR1 and hGluR2) than AMPA itself (Ki = 14.7, 25.1, and 1820 nM for hGluR1, hGluR2 and hGluR5 respectively).
A D-fucopyranose having alpha-configuration at its anomeric centre.
A 7-hydroxyflavonol with additional hydroxy groups at positions 3, 3' and 4'.
A member of the class of  (trifluoromethyl)benzenes  that is p-cresol in which the methyl group is perfluorinated. It is a metabolite of the drug fluoxetine.

A retinoid obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of all-trans retinoic acid and the anilino group of 4-hydroxyaniline. Synthetic retinoid agonist. Antiproliferative, antioxidant and anticancer agent with a long half-life in vivo. Apoptotic effects appear to be mediated by a mechanism distinct from that of 'classical' retinoids.
A L-fucopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
An aromatic ketone in which the two substituents on the carbonyl C atom are phenyl and ethyl.
The L-enantiomer of fucitol. It is found in nutmeg.
An oxazoline derivative having an oxo group at the 2-position and an N-{[(5-nitro-2-furyl)methylene]amino} substituent.
The pyranose form of D-quinovose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position .
A zwitterion resulting from the transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the glycyl amino group of glycyl-AMP; major species at pH 7.3.
An alkylbenzene that is benzene having one of its aromatic hydrogens substituted by a propyl group.
An aromatic amino acid consisting of anthranilic acid carrying an N-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl substituent. An analgesic and anti-inflammatory, it is used in rheumatic disorders.
A  butan-4-olide that is tetrahydrofuran substituted by an oxo group at position 2.
A hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone that is 1,4-naphthoquinone having three hydroxy substituents placed at the 2-, 5- and 7-positions.
A GDP-L-galactose having beta-configuration at the anomeric centre of the L-galactose fragment.
A triazole that is benzonitrile substituted by a (1S,2R)-3-(4-fluorophenyl)-2-hydroxy-1-(1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)propyl group at position 4.
An ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the amino group of (2R)-1-aminopropan-2-ol.
An aminobenzoic acid carrying an amino group at position 3.
A dihydroxypyrrolidine that is 5-methylpyrrolidine-3,4-diol bearing a {[(1R)-2-hydroxy-1-phenylethyl]amino}methyl substituent at position 2.
An organofluorine compound that is beta-L-fucose in which the hydroxy group at position 2 is replaced by fluorine.
